My good friend and fellow designer @michelleuberreste introduced @virginiaanneburton , a fabulous Harley Quinn cosplayer, and I recently. Virginia was on the hunt for a custom plague doctor mask to go with her cosplay. I had so much fun making and painting this one of a kind leather plague doctor mask for her and LOVE how this fabulous photoshoot with @tlmedge went!! 

Funny fact, my masters and Phd programs were in epidemiology, which is basically a modern day plague doctor, and leather mask making is what got me into leather design over 15 years ago. I feel like it all has come full circle now and am surprised it’s taken me this long to make a plague doctor mask ü§£üñ§ 
I’ve always wanted to have a segment of my brand that was a mask emporium. Maybe I will explore that idea again! 

Swipe to see detail pics, like an up close of the bi-color hand stitching and ombre paintjob!

The Pull of the Stars by Emma Donoghue‚ú®
Published ~ 21st July 2020
Rating ~ ‚≠êÔ∏è‚≠êÔ∏è‚≠êÔ∏è‚≠êÔ∏è

Synopsis 
:
Dublin, 1918. In a country doubly ravished by war & disease, Nurse Julia Power works at an understaffed hospital in the city centre, where expectant mothers who have come down with an unfamiliar flu are quarantined together. Into Julia’s stressful world step two outsiders : Doctor Kathleen Lynn, on the run from the police , and a young volunteer helper Bridie Sweeney .
In the darkness and intensity of this tiny ward , over the course of three days these women change each others lives in unexpected ways . They lose patients to this baffling pandemic , but they also Shepard new life into a fearful world . With tireless , tenderness and humanity , carers & mothers alike somehow do their impossible work . 

Review ~ 
This book from the beginning was startling . The similarities between the 1918 & 2020 pandemic are each as devasting as each other .. a deadly flu that is being spread by love , touch & kindness . 
We follow nurse Julia over three exhausting days in a maternity ward that fits no more than a few beds in where she works tirelessly to save these mothers and their newborns . I felt raw with emotion for these mothers giving birth in a terrifying era where even to have privacy is denied . Although the mothers did not know each other there was real compassion between them . 
This is a brilliantly written book , it is evident how much research Emma has done , the detail in the midwifery parts are at times hard to read at the same time utterly astonishing that this was a reality . 
I loved this book , the characters in it are so vivid , such ordinary daily acts that are quite extraordinary . 
A story that will stay with me long after the last page ‚ôàÔ∏è#emmadonoghue #bookstagram #pandemic #booklover #bookworm #books #reading #reviews

node.text:
The pure joy of his first soft play in 6 months üòçüòç

Can't say I was thrilled at the idea of soft play but it was handled as well as it could be with limited numbers, hand sanitiser and temperature checks.

At the end of the day we're living with this thing for potentially 2 years plus so we've all got to live within our own risk appetites. For us his social development and motor skills are important and we're as low risk as can be.

No doubt come October we'll go backwards and be less confident during winter/flu/3rd trimester but until then we will try and enjoy what we can; family, friends, outdoor get togethers, restaurants, swimming, soft play, parks and a much needed family holiday.

Not everyone can, or will want to do those things so most importantly of all is just remembering to be kind to others and don't judge (except the anti vaxxers and anti maskers and illegal ravers they can do one üòÇüòÇ)

node.text:
Limited Edition prints now available on shally.art/store (link in bio!). 

“Standing Still”

Across the oceans and deep blue sea, nothing but emptiness all I could see
The wind kisses across my cheek, I hear the sound of ropes that creak.
I’m reminded of what I left behind, a town of chaos – a city of crime
Of guns and fire and stabbing wounds, the dusty sun and clouded moon
Of prisons and shackles – I broke free, on the search to find my glee
I can’t confess, I can’t complain, my body’s too numb to feel the pain
A ship of sorts, a broken venture, prepping up for a new adventure
Air is clean, the scene is vivid. The night is long but the dreams are timid
“We’re almost there, that’s the hill”, I saw a rock standing still
A new beginning or a lost chapter? A sitting duck or a wild raptor?
Onwards, upwards and steering ahead, crossing the wretched “isle of dead”
History are lessons that I hold near, longing a new home by fighting the fear
Not the same old drama, not the same old drill, no more orders of shoot to kill
A new world awaits us behind the hill, braving the waves – we’re standing still

Poetry by: @underwaterfall_poet

node.text:
When will our society finally stop resisting our present circumstances? 
When are we going to care for each others without sacrificing members of our communities in the name of an economy based on greed? 
We are in the middle of a freaking Pandemic! It’s going to take time and lots of patience before we can go back to the “ NORMAL” we know... 
If you define yourself as a Virtuous Responsible Leader you should want the same exact level of care and safety for yourself and all the people in your Organization. It’s called RECIPROCITY! Why would you think it’s acceptable to offer anything less to others than what you want for yourself? 
As a LEADER you are supposed to LEAD not FORCE... You have to provide the resources needed for your Organization to operate safely. Your job is to SIMPLIFY operations in order to relieve anxiety, build trust, and empower your people so they have the EXTRA ENERGY needed during these challenging times. Change is always stressful. Change calls for a high level of adaptation which has nothing to do with the replication of what WAS before... And please! Stop believing technology will save us! The key components to tackle this new challenge will be Relationships, change, and creativity. Forget about conformity and standardization while we are exploring uncharted territories! In times of uncertainty Humans need Humans more than ever. Stop judging, as it only separates! We need UNITY to overcome this worldwide challenge. node.text:
The Pattern Blog⁠
The Reopening of Schools - Part One⁠
⁠
Welcome to 2020. The first question is, do you want to send your child back to school in the middle of a Pandemic? The second question is, how is your school district opening – remote learning, in-person, or a new term – a hybrid approach – an alternation between in-person and remote learning.  If your child does not go back to school, who will look after them if you have to go to work? What is your broadband connection in case your child is learning virtually? Can it be shared between everyone in the household? How does the average parent address the multitude of questions raised? How do teachers navigate these issues? Administrators? Every stakeholder has a legitimate set of concerns, especially watching the reports of school districts that have tried and failed to re-open.⁠
⁠
Read more on the Pattern Blog: #LinkInBio⁠
https://www.pattern-for-progress.org/the-reopening-of-schools-part-one/

Aseem Malhotra has a simple, evidence-based plan to rapidly improve your metabolic health, help with normal immune function, and likely reduce the risk of severe effects from COVID-19.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Dr Aseem Malhotra is a leading NHS-trained cardiologist and a pioneer of lifestyle medicine. He has been at the forefront of citing the health conditions which make us vulnerable to the worst effects of Covid-19. Obesity, Type 2 diabetes and heart disease are high among them – and all indicators of poor metabolic health.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
The good news is that in just 21 days we can prevent, improve and even potentially reverse many of the underlying risk factors that exacerbate how infections, including Covid-19, affect us and improve our ability to recover from them.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Giving us the evidence-based science behind the plan, Dr Malhotra joins How To Academy to share simple changes to our diet as well as daily exercise and stress relief can have remarkable results in improving our markers for metabolic health, even helping to put Type 2 diabetes into remission, reduce risk factors for heart disease, decrease weight and enhance vitality.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
In this livestreamed event exploring the ideas in his new book The 21 Day Immunity Plan, he will show how to start the journey to a healthier and longer life.‚†Ä

This event takes place on Sun 30 August at 6:30pm BST.‚†Ä

node.text:
Host (2020) was as concise and as terrifying as a horror movie could be. The movie felt extremely real. I liked how it was a shot, through zoom, but it could have been better. I really thought it was unique that the film was shot in real time. This a definitely a movie you would want to watch during quarantine, being this film takes place during the Coronavirus pandemic. They make a few references to the current pandemic. This film had many scenes that will make you jump. I thought these scenes were executed phenomenally. One scene that I thought was great was when the filter face was floating in mid air, and the girl reached for the face and it turned to face her. This demon was as scary as any demon that we have seen it quite sometime. This film focused more on scaring the life out of you than anything else. The characters lacked substance but that wasn’t the point of this film. The final scene, although predictable, has the ability to make you jump 12 feet in the air. Again, this film has many scenes that are capable of scaring just about anybody. Host got right to the point, wasting no time, finishing with a terrifying 7.6.

#Repost @danny_the_vet
• • • • • •
Danny Chambers - Veterinary Surgeon

Some pet health Facebook groups and Instagram accounts have been spreading the rumour that in order to make more profit, vets force owners to vaccinate dogs every year instead of every three years. 

This is simply incorrect. 

The vaccine in question is called DHP and protects dogs against Distemper, Infectious Hepatitis, and Parvovirus. 

The DHP vaccine only needs to be given every three years but vets are NOT recommending it more often than is necessary.

In a poll of over 1000 UK vets asking how often they vaccinate against DHP, over 98% administer the DHP vaccine every three years, with some saying they only give it every five years. 

Vets who give annual vaccinations are usually vaccinating against Leptospirosis which dogs can catch anywhere they come in contact with water contaminated with rat urine- canals, lakes, farms, pretty much everywhere. It can also infect humans and is known as Weil's disease. 

Don't believe the scare stories- if you have concerns regarding vaccinating your pet please speak to your vet who will be happy to discuss this with you... don't rely on Facebook groups or Instagram accounts that are spreading false rumours!

There are those who want to see a world with no vaccines. Well, this coronavirus pandemic has shown us what the world is like without just one specific vaccine. 

Please share to spread the world - vaccines work!

As part of emergency measures to confront the spread of coronavirus, all #schools and #nurseries have been closed and children were asked to stay home as much as possible. It has been an especially challenging time for children with ASD and their parents.

As children's routines are interrupted by the #coronavirus pandemic, they might exhibit more challenging behaviors.

node.text: Ojala se les devuelva todo a esos chinos come m.
Ojala se les devuelva todo a esos chinos come m.

US intelligence has found out that officials in the Chinese city of Wuhan kept senior officials in Beijing in the dark for weeks about the coronavirus outbreak that resulted in the pandemic. The intelligence contains indisputable evidence of the local cover-up attempt, the officials say.

The reports also say that when the Chinese Communist Party learned about the virus, it sought to obscure the full extent of that knowledge from the rest of the world. They also believe that there came a point where China President Xi Jinping did become aware of the full extent of the outbreak in Wuhan and realised that coronavirus was spreading but continued to downplay the situation publically.

These findings are on the lines of the Trump administration's repeated accusations against China. The Trump administration has for long looked into the possibility that the novel coronavirus spread from a Chinese laboratory rather than a market, but has presented no proof to back up that theory. 

For more news updates, stay tuned with Socialist-Today.

node.text:
Often we tend to see the difficulties bigger than they actually are. If we believe we have failed is normally worse üòµ

There's when we started punishing ourselves over and over again. And, our limiting beliefs make a party making us feel like we aren't enough, like we just have activated the countdown to end the üó∫Ô∏è

Once ago, I heard the philosophy of K.I.S.S. and it is so true that it's applicable everyday and by everyone.

Don't make the problem bigger than it is. If it is a problem then accept it as it is. Thus the solution will come customised for the size and colour of the issue matter.

Enjoy life no matter what

PANDEMIC-IS-GLOBAL-134307 @factsweshouldknow'.

Photo by we should know... on August 23, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'The Spanish Flu 1918) Argument Historically, viruses have been named after locations. Examples include the Spanish flu, the Ebola, and Zika viruses. BUT, "locations" do not mean "origins". The Spanish Flu: Instead of being virus named after its place of origin, got its name because Spain was the first to report that its citizens were dying from the flu. The Spanish called it the French flu. Researchers believe it may have originated in Kansas. Diseases were anchored to specific areas through their names BUT: Ebola virus not the Congolese disease (1976). Lyme disease not the American disease (1975).'.

Photo by we should know... on August 23, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'The world has progressed. We're a lot more aware of the consequences of being cavalier with our words. WHO's guidelines are clear: While identifying a new disease by its place of origin seems intuitive, history demonstrates that doing so can harm the people who live there. For all these reasons in 2015, the World Health Organization established a new set of best practices for naming diseases. The WHO sought to abandon associating places with a disease. @factsweshouldknow'.

node.text:
Straight Shootin' Rant Episode 28 - Why do conspiracy theories have fans?

YouTube Link - https://youtu.be/mPTsX3W25-8
Mixcloud link (Audio only) - https://www.mixcloud.com/StraightShootinLJA/straight-shootin-rant-episode-28-why-do-conspiracy-theories-have-fans/

On this episode Straight Shootin' LJA gives his views about Conspiracy Theories (inspired by John Oliver's Last Week Tonight segment) and why he thinks they have fans/believers, especially during the coronavirus/Covid-19 pandemic.

Straight Shootin' LJA also gives his opinion on John Oliver's encouragement to believe mainstream sources, but encourages people to look at supermarkets, government and also trusted media sources abusing trust so much, that they've basically driven people into believing conspiracy theories.

Also this is a general opinion & is not aimed at anyone in particular unless otherwise stated.

node.text:
I know this pandemic has changed all of our lives in so many ways. For me I’ve been able to be home in Scotland and luckily been able to work from home, I usually work away a lot. Hence never being here to actually sort my house out. I’m enjoying wording from home, my house is quiet during the day giving me the time to work. But I felt like I was letting my home office get very messy, so today I took everything off the table. I had ordered some new bits for my office from Amazon, I gave everything a good scrub down with some fabulosa electrify how apt! I feel so much better about the space now. I do want to get a desk but haven’t quite found one that fits. I am lucky that my dinette can be turned in to a home office so I’m not encroaching so much on the rest of the house. 

How is everyone else feeling about their home offices? Are you all enjoying or hating working from home?

Hart Main is a 14-year old that came up with the idea of manly scented candles when he was teasing his sister about the girly scented ones she was selling for a school fundraiser. 

Although she didn't expect him to fully pursue the manly scented candles idea himself, he did, and the idea has turned into a nationwide success. Main put in an initial investment of $100, his parents put in $200, and they all worked together to develop the candles as a group.

node.text:
The PM’s Office has consistently refused to divulge any information about the PM-CARES fund’s spendings, citing that it is not a “public authority” under the Right to Information Act, 2005.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
However, file notings accessed by RTI activists show that the Ministry of Corporate Affairs had declared that the fund was set up by the Central government on the day the fund was created, thus making it a public authority under the ambit of Section 2(h) of the RTI Act, 2005. The PM-CARES Fund was set up on March 27, 2020, as an emergency measure for disaster relief during the coronavirus pandemic.‚†Ä
‚†Ä

node.text: I am an English Lit. Major but I have always held on to this belief that Poems are more beautiful when they are raw and imperfect . Too much emphasis on the form and structure make them superfluous .
It's a beautiful one . Like always . I love reading your poems . üíõ
@walnutgirl03 that's so nice of you to say!‚ù§Ô∏è
This is one of the best things I've read all quarantine, thank you so very muchüíì
@walnutgirl03 that's so nice of you to say!‚ù§Ô∏è

Yes, it is a sonnet. Count the lines and scan it; it’s not perfect, but I’ve not yet written a perfect poem. If you know any English Lit majors, do show them and challenge them to write a #PandemicSonnet or even a villanelle. Why not? It could be fun. Tag me if you do, because poems are more interesting when we read them and write them together.

As always, you like what you see here, and want to see it continue, please tell a friend, spread the word. My website is linked in bio. You can also dm me your email or write me at hamraazATprotonmailDOTcom¬† That way, if this site gets shut down like my FB page did, I won’t be whispering to myself in the dark.

node.text: The whole world is in the same boat
The whole world is in the same boat

South Africa's retail industry is feeling the pain from the coronavirus pandemic on two fronts-store closures during lockdown and the sharply reduced purchasing power of households. 

South Africa, the continent's most industrialized economy, went into strict lockdown at the end of March, with people only allowed to shop for essential items such as food, medicine and winter clothing.
It is also the African country that has been hardest hit by COVID-19, with more than 600,000 cases and at least 2,500 deaths. 

Restrictions have been gradually rolled back since June. Alcohol and tobacco sales were allowed to resume this week and, generally, business is now almost back to normal. --AFP

Exercising for even 5 mins daily goes a long way! üéà
Send me your pictures for promotion
Exercising for even 5 mins daily goes a long way! üéà

Whether you choose to do yoga for 10 minutes, follow a dance workout for 30 minutes or even go for a short walk every evening -- setting aside some time every day for physical activity is good not only for your physical health but also for your mental health! 

From improving moods to helping get better sleep and relieving stress, regular exercise is a good way to get started on your self-care journey!

________________________________ 

SELF-CARE WEEK üå∏

In these strange times it is important now, more than ever, to take time out of our stressful days to take care of ourselves. 

Whether you feel like you're busy with work all day, or stuck at home surrounded by people you don't get along with, make self-care a part of your daily routine! 

This week, Identity is focussing on self-care with little tips on how to ensure that you are looking after your mental health. 

If you have any questions or would like to further discuss looking after your mental health, DM us!

node.text:
Dear subscribers, friends, readers, colleagues,

To our regret, the newest issue of Volume has been delayed, but yes, we are still here and yes, we are still producing. As a matter of fact, the content is now at Irma Boom’s @irma_boom_amsterdam  office to be designed. We took the strange limbo-working from home time to reflect on the Defaults in architecture or maybe the Defaults in society at large. The aftermath of the pandemic will throw us in another long global transition, and architects cannot afford to waste time feeding golden calves. Before we operate, this time we must change the default settings.

How much of us is by default, and how much is by design?

We are again very grateful to our great network of friends who immediately helped to think with us and share their insights, hunches and knowledge. Further to our subscribers who stay with us and remain patient. That will be rewarded with an extra super special supplement ‘Herbarium of Interiors’ we made together with @headgeneve. We expect to release the beginning of September.

For now, we would like to share the effort to change the Default by Massimo Paolini. He wrote a letter to the Mayor (in this case Barcelona) late April as an urgent call to rethink the city as a direct reaction to the Covid pandemic. His plea got immediate response from thousands of supporters and is easily transferable and applicable to any other city in Europe and far beyond. 

Have a look at our latest post on our website.

Enjoy the summer, stay safe and tuned. 

#pandemic #massimopaolini #summer2020 #society #barcelona #reflexion #europe #city #covid #volumemagazine

This is the new threat to biodiversity. Masks. While it is still unclear on its use for stopping the spread of the virus, it is recommended by health officials that we use masks for our own safety & safety of others. Unfortunately, after its use, it is treated like any other disposable which can be thrown around just anywhere and everywhere.

A recent study estimates that in the coming years, our oceans will have more masks floating around than jellyfish! 

Apart from being trash, these masks might transmit diseases to the wildlife that interacts with it. It’ll eventually circle back to us. We don’t want another pandemic, do we? Please opt for reusable masks. Be responsible while discarding them. Spread the word. 

Came across this picture on WhatsApp by one Mr.Ramjee. DM for image credit.

Di antaranya untuk mendukung sistem imun (kekebalan tubuh) dari serangan virus, bakteri, dan kuman lainnya. Juga untuk kesehatan jantung atau yang sering disebut penyakit kardiovaskuler (jantung dan pembuluh darah), serta untuk kecantikan seperti membuat sampo dan menghaluskan kulit. Adanya pandemi Coronavirus disease 19 (COVID- 19), membuat orang mencari tahu lebih banyak produk obat-obatan, minuman, dan makanan yang bisa mempercepat proses penyembuhan penyakit menula ini. vco menjadi salah satu pilihan yang bisa digunakan.'.

Virgin coconut oil (VCO) adalah minyak kelapa yang diekstraksi dan bermanfaat bagi kesehatan. VCO dibuat dengan kopra, atau daging kelapa kering yang dikeluarkan dari cangkang dan ditekan untuk mengekstrak minyak alami dengan berbagai manfaat untuk Tubuh Manusia.
•
Jangan lupa untuk mengonsumsi VCO (Virgin Coconut Oil) untuk memelihara kesehatan kita, meningkatkan imunitas kita serta melindungi diri kita dikondisi #pandemic saat ini.

@aesthetic__bird I will ... with so many people inspiring a commoner like me... I feed overwhelmed ... learning in this journey of last 4 months was immense and humbling... pulled me down from the ivory tower and made me connect ... love this...‚ù§Ô∏è
Let me start by sharing how I met the person who inspires me the most .

@narayanshankerbhatt the moment we began speaking on chat,I could feel a positive connection. The kind of person that you,so passionate and so full of energy, always inquisitive to learn new things. Your enthusiasm is infectious I must say‚ù§Ô∏è Not just that ,the way you analyse things,your diverse interests,movies,books, history, singing, the interest you take to appreciate finest of things üòÄ. I have a lot to look upto and learn from you. Indeed Universe has plans. We simply don't meet people. Everything happens for a reason. I always believed and now ,I believe it even moreüòç
@tharinigowda I tooo truly believe it... let the karma play its dice... odds and evens are for nature to decide... it is a black swan moment‚ù§Ô∏è

It was a initial days of lock down and me being a history buff noticed an article on mythical creature " Yazhi"... it was spelt differently and I just did a correction . Immediately I recieved a thank u note from @tharinigowda . She is inspirer to the core. She is mountaineer, traveller, food blogger, historian. Above all a extremely super human being. We got connected and till date it has been helluva inspiration to cheer up. Whether it is banter on Quantum physics , or on History she is part of it. She ensures that interest is maintained in conversation.  She is a nature lover and conservationist. Our mutual admiration can be gauged from the fact that we have never spoken ( as we never felt need) , but maintained good vibes thru out... @tharinigowda ‚ù§Ô∏è

"No amount of darkness can hide a spark of light."
Life is a journey and we meet all sort of people in this journey. Some people will let you down, pull you back and will always point out the negative thing in you. Whereas some people will support you, guide you and will always be there for you.
I personally feel that both the kinds are important for a healthy living. On one hand positivity keeps you happy and peaceful and on the other hand negativity shows you the reality of life.
We have faced a lot of negativity in 2020 and i hope you all find positivity in little things.
Mention down the happy moments of your life and tag the person/people who made you happy and feel positive!

Rajshri Deshpande¬†who played the role of Ganesh Gaitonde in the web series called Sacred Games  is now trying to raise funds to renovate the Zilla Parishad School in Pimpalgaon Pandhari, Aurangabad. node.text:
Gauhati University on Saturday issued Standard Operating Procedure (SOP) for final semester exams which are scheduled to be held in September.
.
“Promotion of Intermediate semester students will be considered on the basis of internal assessment marks and theory marks in the earlier semesters subject to the fact that they have completed the online submission of examination forms, an official statement said.
.
While final semester undergraduate (UG) and postgraduate (PG) semester students will be evaluated using a 50-50 formula, 50% marks from offline exams and the remaining 50% from internal assessments.
.
“Final semester examinations will be conducted in blended mode maintaining COVID-19 protocol and the relevant SOP published by the UGC for the purpose,” Gauhati University said.
.
The question paper(s) for the final semester examinations will cover the whole syllabus but the students will be required to attempt questions for 50% marks only.
.
The remaining 50% marks will be calculated on the basis of internal assessment, the University said.
.
“The Heads of respective Academic Departments, G.U. are requested to finalise the mode of action in relation to dissertation in consultation will Controller of Examinations, Gauhati University,” it added.
.
.

node.text:
ü§î Hurdles ü§î
Day 23 of @_thecottonshop #imthemaker challenge
•
These are probably some of the most recent hurdles I’ve had to deal with, some of them probably seem really trivial and a lot of people have similar things going on but a hurdle is a hurdle none the less.
•
For me the pandemic, being pregnant and isolated, whilst dealing with BPD and OCD (which decided to go into overdrive from about 11 weeks) has been my biggest hurdle to overcome. Looking back now I’m almost 30 weeks I can see I definitely got through the hardest days and *touch wood* have come out the other side a lot stronger.
•
Fellow mamas to be, new mamas, seasoned mums, small business mamas, other people who are dealing with difficult times and mental health issues, I take my hat off to you, you are the real mvps. You are doing great ‚ú®

Koordinator Masyarakat Anti Korupsi Indonesia (MAKI), Boyamin Saiman pun turut menyorot keberadaan dua alat penting yang hilang akibat kebakaran tersebut.

.
Kedua benda itu adalah CCTV dan alat sadap yang terpasang di gedung Kejagung. Kebakaran, katanya, akan mengakibatkan rekaman aktivitas pegawai hilang terbakar oleh api. Apalagi gedung Kejagung habis terbakar selama 11 jam.

.
Sorotan Boyamin lantas difokuskan pada kasus besar yang tengah ditangani Kejagung, salah satunya kasus penangkapan buron kelas kakap Djoko Tjandra.

.
Di mana dalam kasus ini, jaksa Pinangki Sirna Malasari resmi ditetapkan sebagai tersangka. Sementara kantor jaksa Pinangki ada di dalam gedung yang terbakar.

.
Artinya, ada kemungkinan rekaman CCTV dan alat sadap aktivitas jaksa Pinangki akan hilang.

.
“Paling tidak oknum Jaksa P itu kan juga berkantor di situ kan dulunya. Paling tidak kegiatan-kegiatan dia tuh apa aja, kan karena nyatanya ada dugaan Anita dan R itu yang juga diduga mengantar Djoko Tjandra itu kan juga pernah bertemu di kantor itu kan,” urainya kepada Kantor Berita Politik RMOL, Minggu (23/8).

.
“Setidaknya CCTV yang kira-kira merekam kegiatan oknum Jaksa P ini kan juga sudah menjadi hilang kalau memang belum diamankan loh ya," ujar Boyamin

.
Selengkapnya:
https://www.gelora.co/2020/08/maki-jaksa-pinangki-pernah-berkantor-di.html?m=1

.
